+# Solution: SIGN function return type mismatch
+
+## Root Cause
+
+T-SQL's `SIGN` function returns the **same data type as its input** (per MSDN). C#'s `Math.Sign` always returns `int`. When the input column is `decimal` (or any non-`int` numeric type), SQL Server returns a `decimal` value, but EF Core's materializer calls `SqlDataReader.GetInt32()` expecting `int`, causing `InvalidCastException: Unable to cast System.Decimal to System.Int32`.
+
+The existing code called `TranslateFunction("SIGN", arg, nullTypeMapping: true)`, which passed `method.ReturnType` (`int`) as the declared CLR type but emitted no `CAST` in SQL, leaving a mismatch between what SQL Server actually returns and what the reader expects.
+
+## Change Description
+
+Replaced the `TranslateFunction("SIGN", ...)` call with a dedicated `TranslateSign` method (following the same pattern as `TranslateTruncate` and `TranslateRound` in the same file). The new method:
+
+1. Emits `SIGN(<arg>)` with the argument's own type and type mapping (so the function call is correctly typed in SQL).
+2. Wraps the result in `CAST(... AS int)` for all argument types that are not already `int` (`decimal`, `double`, `float`, `long`, `sbyte`, `short`). This makes the SQL expression type match `int` — the C# return type of every `Math.Sign` overload.
+
+The CAST is omitted when the argument is already `int` (SIGN of an int still returns int in T-SQL), avoiding a no-op cast.
+
+## Files Edited
+
+- `src/EFCore.SqlServer/Query/Internal/Translators/SqlServerMathTranslator.cs` — core fix
+- `test/EFCore.Specification.Tests/Query/Translations/MathTranslationsTestBase.cs` — added `Sign_decimal()` test method to the shared base
+- `test/EFCore.SqlServer.FunctionalTests/Query/Translations/MathTranslationsSqlServerTest.cs` — updated expected SQL for `Sign()` and `Sign_float()` (now emit CAST), added `Sign_decimal()` override with expected SQL
+
+## Precedent Usage
+
+**Query 1:** `"SIGN function return type cast int decimal math"`
